Prepare the dataset.

Preparing the DV

Our dependent variable (DV) is COVID vaccine dosage (“Dosage”).
Older adults received: < 3 doses; 3 doses; > 3 doses of COVID-19 vaccine. Those 3 levels should be ordered.
Make sure our DV is recognized as a ordered factor because we are going for ordinal logistic regression.

covid$Dosage <- as_factor(covid$Dosage, ordered = TRUE)
covid$Dosage_nozero <- as_factor(covid$Dosage_nozero, ordered = TRUE)

Note Dosage_nozero is a special-case DV. It does not contain cases that received 0 doses. We may or may not explore this DV within this file. 

Our source file was an imported SPSS .sav file. Labeling from SPSS may interfere with R processing. Transform applicable categorical variables into factors.

# Treat haven label for categorical variables, if Haven is causing trouble

Preparing the IV: demographics

Similarly, let’s make sure we get to see which level is significant, compared to the reference level. (Sometimes model output omits detailed levels)

covid$region <- factor(covid$region, levels = 1:3, labels = c("1HK", "2KL", "3NT"))
covid$education <- factor(covid$education, levels = 1:3, labels = c("3Tertiary", "2Secondary", "1Primary or below"))
covid$marital <- factor(covid$marital, levels = 1:4, labels = c("1Single", "2Married", "3Divorced", "4Widowed"))
covid$income <- factor(covid$income, levels = 0:2, labels = c("1No Income", "1Less Than 25K", "More than 25K"))
covid$employment <- factor(covid$employment, levels = 1:5, labels = c("1Full Time", "2Part Time", "3Retired", "4Unemployed", "5Houswife"))
covid$marital <- relevel(covid$marital, ref = 2)

Some other categorical predictors need this similar treatment as well. We will do this when we get there.

A VIF > 10 may be a sign for problematic multicollinearity.

Once we remove the interaction, the VIF looks okay! Seems like it indeed was the introduction of the gender*age interaction term that caused us some trouble.
Mean-centering can remedy this situation. Additionally, mean-centering age helps make age more interpretable: now the effect of other predictors is when age is held at mean value instead of 0 (which as you know, 0-years old makes little intuitive sense in this study!).

Mean-center age, gender and a new interaction term with the centered variables

covid$age_centered <- scale(covid$age, scale = FALSE)
covid$gender_numeric <- as.numeric(covid$gender) - 1  #1 = male, 2 = female
covid$gender_centered <- scale(covid$gender_numeric, scale = FALSE)

covid$interaction_centered <- covid$age_centered * covid$gender_centered

The Analysis

Basic ordinal logistic regression models that assume proportional odds

We first explore the basic, proportional odds assumption models.
In the context of our dataset: remember we have 3 levels within our DV:
< 3 doses,
= 3 doses, and
> 3 doses.

In ordinal logistic regression, we study what effects a predictor has on the DV:
Will this predictor make it more, or less likely to be in a higher category.
By proportional odds, we assume that this likelihood applies equally to all thresholds:
It is equally likely to move from <3 doses to =3 doses, and =3 doses to >3 doses.
We cross 2 thresholds with 3 levels, but the likelihood (the estimates we get) when crossing 2 thresholds are assumed to stay the same.

Using polr()

When we assume this, we can calculate by using polr():

We can also create a custom function to show odds ratio in a forest plot:

# Custom function for forest plot
# notice VGAM give intercept in both OR and CI
create_forest_plot <- function(model) {

  odds_ratios <- exp(coef(model))
  conf_int <- exp(confint(model))

  # Remove intercepts from odds_ratios 
  odds_ratios_no_intercept <- odds_ratios[-c(1:2)]  

  or_df <- data.frame(
    Predictor = names(odds_ratios_no_intercept),
    OR = odds_ratios_no_intercept,
   Lower_CI = conf_int[, 1],
   Upper_CI = conf_int[, 2]
  )
  or_df$Predictor <- fct_rev(factor(or_df$Predictor, levels = names(odds_ratios)))
  or_df$OR_CI_Label <- sprintf("%.2f (%.2f, %.2f)", or_df$OR, or_df$Lower_CI, or_df$Upper_CI)
  or_df$Significant <- ifelse(or_df$Lower_CI > 1 | or_df$Upper_CI < 1, TRUE, FALSE)
  
  # Create the forest plot using ggplot2
  ggplot(or_df, aes(x = OR, y = Predictor, OR)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = Significant), size = 3) +  # Highlight significant points in color
    geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = Lower_CI, xmax = Upper_CI, color = Significant), height = 0.2) +  # Add horizontal error bars
    geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +  # Add vertical line at OR = 1 for reference
    geom_text(aes(label = OR_CI_Label, x = OR, y = Predictor), hjust = -0.2, vjust = 1.2, size = 3) +  # Add OR and CI labels
    scale_color_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "grey", "TRUE" = "blue")) +  # Color significant points blue
    
   labs(x = "Odds Ratio (log scale)", 
        y = "Predictor", 
        title = "Forest Plot of Odds Ratios and 95% Confidence Intervals") +
   scale_x_log10() +  # Log scale for odds ratios
   theme_minimal()+
    theme(
      plot.margin = margin(10, 20, 10, 20),  # Add padding to all sides of the plot
      legend.position = "none"  # Remove legend for significance coloring
    )
  

}

Now call the function:

create_forest_plot(basic_model2)

Based on the estimates and the plot, we see that the direction of estimates met our expectations: participants who are older, less educated, living in public housing seem to receive fewer doses, which aligns well with what we generally know about older adult population.
But does the proportional odds assumption actually hold?

Testing proportional odds assumption

We can check this assumption with Brant test using brant()

The results of the Brant test shows age, education (and the omnibus test) were significant. The assumption is unlikely to hold.
Additionally, consider the context and theoretical background of this dataset.
It is not practical to assume that older adults’ motivation behind vaccination behavior, especially about change in such behavior, is same for changing from<3 doses to =3 doses (which is government mandate), and from =3 doses to >3 doses. A model that does not require such assumption is preferred.
Meet Generalized Ordered Logit Model.

Generalized Ordered Logit Model (w/o proportional odds assumption) using vglm()

1 Demographics-only

The generalized ordered logit model (or cumulative logistic regression model) will break the assumption where “two thresholds should hold same value”, and allow the predictors to have different estimates upon two thresholds.
Demographics-only model using vglm().
Be advised: by default this model assumes you will compare lower DV category against higher. Use reverse = TRUE argument to flip that back. Also pay attention to what exactly the estimates/probability means: It is not the predictor that gained more levels; it is the DV!

cumulative_basic_model <- vglm(Dosage ~ region + gender_centered + age_centered + interaction_centered + education + marital + income + 
                              public_housing + living_with_family, 
                            family = cumulative(link = "logitlink",parallel = FALSE, reverse = TRUE), data = covid)

summary(cumulative_basic_model)

Again, pay attention to the model output where:
Names of linear predictors: logitlink(P[Y>=2]), logitlink(P[Y>=3])
This means the estimates of the predictors (and odds ratios) were comparing higher to lower, which is what we usually expect.

The output seems confusing with every single variable having two lines: variable:1 and variable:2.
A way that may help understand is by imagining having two separate binomial logistic regressions.
The generalized ordered logit model gave us additional insight that was hidden in previous models:

Example 1: Gender
Coefficients: Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)
gender_centered:1 -0.008311 0.142359 -0.058 0.95344
gender_centered:2 -0.192867 0.093633 -2.060 0.03941 *
Gender was previous not significant (p = 0.09).
In this new model:
For <3 doses to =3 doses, gender had no effect.
But for =3 doses to >3 doses, gender was significant (p= 0.03).
For and only for =3 doses to >3 doses, females were less likely than males to being in a higher category.

Example 2: Age
Coefficients: Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)
age_centered:1 -0.041775 0.008318 -5.023 5.10e-07 ***
age_centered:2 -0.005536 0.006084 -0.910 0.36284
Similarly, Age was previously significant (p = 0.002).
But where exactly did this effect play out?
Turns out, for <3 doses to =3 doses, age was significant (p = 5.10e-07). As people get older, they are less likely to being in a higher category.
However, for =3 doses to >3 doses, age was not significant.
Age affected decisions to jump from <3 doses to =3 doses (and it was contributing negatively); but not for decisions to jump from =3 doses to >3 doses.

Example 3: Public Housing
Coefficients: Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)
public_housing:1 -0.313489 0.130283 -2.406 0.01612 *
public_housing:2 -0.239526 0.086526 -2.768 0.00564 **
In this case, public_housing is significant for both thresholds of the DV, meaning that: for both <3 doses to =3 doses AND =3 doses to >3 doses, living in public housing decreases the likelihood of being in a higher category.
This is also consistent with the Brant test earlier where p = 0.67 was observed for public_housing, meaning this predictor likely did not violate the proportional odds assumption.

Beware
Take note that using generalized ordered logit model did not contradict our previous conclusions; rather this model refined these conclusions, provided us with a more detailed, in-depth view of where the change occurred:
Which one of the thresholds did a certain predictor affect? From <3 doses to =3 doses? From =3 doses to >3 doses? Or perhaps both?

Similarly, we can generate an odds ratio plot:

create_forest_plot_vgam <- function(model) {
  
  odds_ratios <- exp(coef(model))
  conf_int <- exp(confint(model))
  
  or_df <- data.frame(
    Predictor = names(odds_ratios),
    OR = odds_ratios,
    Lower_CI = conf_int[, 1],
    Upper_CI = conf_int[, 2]
  )
  
  or_df$Predictor <- fct_rev(factor(or_df$Predictor, levels = names(odds_ratios)))
  or_df$OR_CI_Label <- sprintf("%.2f (%.2f, %.2f)", or_df$OR, or_df$Lower_CI, or_df$Upper_CI)
  or_df$Significant <- ifelse(or_df$Lower_CI > 1 | or_df$Upper_CI < 1, TRUE, FALSE)
  
  # Create the forest plot using ggplot2
  ggplot(or_df, aes(x = OR, y = Predictor, OR)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = Significant), size = 3) +  # Highlight significant points in color
    geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = Lower_CI, xmax = Upper_CI, color = Significant), height = 0.2) +  # Add horizontal error bars
    geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +  # Add vertical line at OR = 1 for reference
    geom_text(aes(label = OR_CI_Label, x = OR, y = Predictor), hjust = -0.2, vjust = 1.2, size = 3) +  # Add OR and CI labels
    scale_color_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "grey", "TRUE" = "blue")) +  # Color significant points blue
    
    labs(x = "Odds Ratio (log scale)", 
         y = "Predictor", 
         title = "Forest Plot of Odds Ratios and 95% Confidence Intervals") +
    scale_x_log10() +  # Log scale for odds ratios
    theme_minimal()+
    theme(
      plot.margin = margin(10, 20, 10, 20),  # Add padding to all sides of the plot
      legend.position = "none"  # Remove legend for significance coloring
    )
  

}
